According to uneducated judges and Francissy headcanon, yes Francis won. According to the official scoring criteria of MMA and reality, Gane won and it's not up for debate. First, let's establish that scoring criteria:
>It shall be noted that a successful takedown is not merely a changing of position, but the establishment of an attack from the use of the takedown. Top and bottom position fighters are assessed more on the impactful/effective result of their actions, more so than their position. This criterion will be the deciding factor in a high majority of decisions when scoring a round.
Understood? Let's begin.
>Round 1 goes to Gane clearly, Gane lands more strikes and lands cleaner than Francis, forward aggression doesn't supercede effective striking
Round 1 Gane 10-9
>Round 2 Gane wins also for the same reason as Round 1. Gane also gets the better of a few clinch exchanges here.
Round 2 Gane 10-9
>Round 3 Gane takes this one too. Striking is negligible in this round although Gane was winning in that realm. Two takedowns from Francis that lead to no offense at all, thus they shall not be taken into account if we're judging based on the official criteria. Gane attempts a kimura which is the only offense on the ground in Round 3.
Round 3 Gane 10-9
>Round 4 could go either way depending on what you value most. Again Gane lands more on the feet, but Francis had 1 successful takedown in this round that led to some GnP. I'll favor Francis just to give him a chance.
Round 4 Francis 10-9
>Round 5 arguably the clearest round for Gane. Lands more offense on the feet, and landed a successful takedown which results in a leglock attempt. Francis lands no significant offense in this round and solely establishes ground control, which isn't weighted according to the official criteria.
Round 5 Gane 10-9.
Gane wins 49-46. Objectively. Feel free to attempt to dispute this

Currently, the U.S. itself accounts for ~25% of global GDP. Combined with NATO and major non-NATO allies, about 60% of world GDP is in the U.S. bloc. And the bulk of the remainder (Brazil, Mexico, India, the GCC, etc.) is still friendly with the U.S.

Ignoring big achievements in the past like putting the first man on the moon or detonating the first atom bomb, the bulk of current scientific progress still comes from the U.S. This is quite relevant in our information economy. Its tech giants in particular have no real equivalent anywhere else, and it still leads the world in research and impact factor by a pretty enormous margin.

English is the most spoken language on the planet, especially among L2, and the de facto language of international business. American films, shows, games, clothes, brands, and other cultural products are ubiquitous in every country it trades with. Hollywood helped conquer the world.

The U.S. dollar is the world's reserve currency. About 80% of international finance is facilitated through it. Past rivals like the Japanese yen and the EU euro have failed quite horribly in their attempts to displace it following the economic stagnations of their home countries (to wit, the European Union is still not at 2007 levels of GDP, and is set for a big crisis if Italy and France continue down their current paths). Plus events revealing the fragility of their systems. We'll have to wait and see for the Chinese RMB, but currently the entirety of the international economy is dependent on U.S. infrastructure.

The sheer advantage the U.S. has over the rest of the planet economically really can't be overemphasized. In 2014-2016, the U.S. basically just flexed (convinced the EU to go with some halfhearted sanctions and slightly increased their own oil production) and it knocked $600 billion off of the Russian economy
